Environment, three layers and a dot env file.

A service's environment variables can come from three places, and they stack in a clear precedence order from lowest to highest. Lowest is the environment baked into the image by the dockerfile. Above that is an env-file, one or more files of key-equals-value lines. And highest is the environment block written directly in the y-a-m-l, which wins over the other two. So if you set a value in both an env-file and the environment block, the environment block is the one that takes effect.

Now, there is a second, separate thing also called dot env, and confusing the two is extremely common. Compose reads a file named dot env sitting next to the compose file, but for a completely different purpose. It substitutes variables into the text of the y-a-m-l itself before parsing. So a value in that dot env file can fill in an image tag or a password placeholder written in the compose file. The clean way to keep them straight is this. The dot env file supplies variables for the compose file's own text, resolved at parse time. An env-file supplies variables for the container's runtime environment, inside the running service. Read the keyword carefully and you will not mix them up.

Variable substitution also supports defaults and requirements. You can give a substitution a default value used when the variable is unset, and you can mark one as required so that compose errors out if it is missing. That required form is a small but powerful safety net, because it turns a silently-empty configuration into a loud failure at startup.
